body:
Killing Eve to get a second season (spy-fy news).

BBC has acquired the second series of the spy thriller Killing Eve. Series one hit on BBC One and as a boxset on BBC iPlayer last month and has seen 26 million downloads of the series so far.

It is of course based on the indie-published Codename Villanelle e-book novellas by Luke Jennings.

Phoebe Waller-Bridge adapted the first series of Killing Eve and will return for the new series in an…

tags: just a short fic I wrote
body:
Curiosity

It’s a surprise when the car stops. Even more so when the driver’s side door opens. Curiosity wins over caution; Villanelle slows to a stop, however she remains poised to shoot or run. After all, she has not forgotten her training — she is simply choosing to ignore it.

The woman who steps out of the car is familiar to her. Eve Polastri. She watches her raise a tentative hand. Many people raise their hands when faced with a gun, as if showing that they themselves have no weapon will change the mind of whoever is before them. Maybe it works with others, but it never has with her. When she intends to kill someone, that person ends up dead, with or without their hands raised.

Polastri’s hand lowers slowly. The two watch one another, equally fascinated, and to an extent equally afraid. Their eyes flicker over one another, Polastri’s gaze fixing on the gun held by the woman who stares a fraction of a second too long at her hair.

One of the women steps forward. But it is not who either of them expected. Villanelle takes a breath, swallows against the unusual lump forming in her throat. Her stomach knots as Polastri advances. Villanelle’s legs are restless, as though her body is trying to remind her of her instinct to run, or her training to fight. She will not run, though. She knows she would regret it if she did. Polastri’s tenacity and nerve fascinate her; it is a rare thing for someone to step towards her, when they know what she can do to them. She would go so far as to say it were unnerving if she considered the other woman a true threat, however she does not sense that she wants her dead. If she had, she would have used that car to crush her. Still, her near certainty that the woman before her does not intend to kill her is not enough to stop the hairs on the back of her neck from standing on end.

The temptation to test the true extent of Polastri’s nerve is overwhelming. Villanelle swallows, raises her gun, wondering if the woman before her will duck, or scream, or try and run. To her surprise, she does none of these things. Polastri seems phased when Villanelle aims the gun at her head. A few micro-expressions betray her inner fears, but they are clouded by a curiosity that matches Villanelle’s own. Raising a hand, and placing the other over her own chest, Polastri continues to study her.

Acting on an impulse, Villanelle draws back her gun. Then, expressionless, she presses its muzzle under her own chin, never once taking her eyes off of Polastri.

“No!”

The word catches her off guard. Surprises a laugh out of her. She wonders if it were genuine or just an instinctual response to seeing someone point a gun at themself.

Regardless, she can’t wait to mull it over. The longer she stays, the more likely she will be caught. And, for the first time in a while, she has found someone who might actually deserve a chance of catching her.

She lifts the gun to her lips, kisses it, then makes her exit.
